      <h1 style="font-size:2.25rem;margin-top:1rem;margin-bottom:0.5rem">PSI vs GPM Explained: What Contractors Need to Know to Choose the Right Pressure Washer</h1>
      <div style="color:#64748b;font-size:0.9rem">June 17, 2026 · 12 min read</div>
    </div>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>Two numbers dominate every pressure washer spec sheet: PSI and GPM. Most contractors know PSI means pressure and GPM means flow, but the relationship between them — and which one matters more for specific jobs — is where the real buying decisions live.</p>
      <p>Misunderstanding these specs is the most expensive mistake a contractor can make when buying a pressure washer. Buying based on PSI alone leads to underpowered machines that clean too slowly. Over-indexing on GPM without considering PSI means you cannot strip tough deposits. This guide explains both specs in practical contracting terms and gives you a framework for matching a machine to your actual job mix.</p>

      <h2>What PSI Actually Means on the Job</h2>
      <p><strong>PSI (pounds per square inch)</strong> measures the force of the water stream hitting the surface. Think of it as the aggressiveness of the cut. Higher PSI strips material faster but also risks damaging the surface if misapplied.</p>
      <p>Here is how PSI ranges map to real contracting work:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>2000–2800 PSI:</strong> Typical electric range. Adequate for house washing, vehicle washing, light mildew removal. Cannot effectively strip paint, remove tire marks from concrete, or clean heavy equipment grease.</li>
        <li><strong>3000–3400 PSI:</strong> Entry-level gas range. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B086XGSLQC?tag=sciencesolved-20">Simpson 3400 PSI / 2.5 GPM residential unit</a> falls here. Handles driveways, fences, and general contractor cleanup. Marginal for commercial paint stripping and concrete restoration.</li>
        <li><strong>3500–4000 PSI:</strong> The professional sweet spot. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07S7H6LGM?tag=sciencesolved-20">Simpson PS60869 PowerShot at 4000 PSI / 3.5 GPM</a> lives here. Strips paint, removes heavy stains, cleans commercial concrete. The added 500 PSI over the 3400-class machine translates to noticeably faster cutting in stripping applications.</li>
        <li><strong>4000–4400 PSI:</strong> Commercial grade. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01KZSGRTE?tag=sciencesolved-20">Simpson 4400 PSI / 4.0 GPM commercial unit</a> and <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0CQQSWJ7Z?tag=sciencesolved-20">VEVOR 4400 PSI / 4.0 GPM</a> operate here. Maximum stripping capability for parking lot restoration, epoxy removal, and heavy industrial cleaning.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The critical rule: never use a 0-degree or 15-degree tip on any surface you care about at PSI above 2500. Always start with a 40-degree wide fan and narrow as needed. Surface damage from high PSI and narrow spray patterns is the #1 source of callbacks for pressure washing contractors.</p>

      <h2>What GPM Actually Means on the Job</h2>
      <p><strong>GPM (gallons per minute)</strong> measures the volume of water flowing through the system. This is the spec that determines how fast you clean a surface. Think of PSI as the sharpness of the knife and GPM as the size of the knife. A sharper knife cuts deeper. A bigger knife covers more area per stroke.</p>
      <p>Here is the practical impact of GPM on cleaning time:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>1.2–1.8 GPM:</strong> Electric washer range. Cleaning a 2,000-square-foot driveway takes 45 minutes to 1 hour. Cleaning a 10,000-square-foot commercial lot takes 5+ hours.</li>
        <li><strong>2.5 GPM:</strong> Entry gas range. The Simpson 3400 / 2.5 GPM cleans that same driveway in 25 minutes and the commercial lot in roughly 3 hours.</li>
        <li><strong>3.5 GPM:</strong> Mid-range pro. The Simpson PS60869 at 3.5 GPM cleans the driveway in 18 minutes and the commercial lot in just over 2 hours.</li>
        <li><strong>4.0 GPM:</strong> Commercial grade. Machines like the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01KZSGRTE?tag=sciencesolved-20">Simpson 4400</a>, <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0G6SXZ7VG?tag=sciencesolved-20">Professional 4200</a>, and <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0CQQSWJ7Z?tag=sciencesolved-20">VEVOR 4400</a> clean a driveway in 12–15 minutes and a 10,000-square-foot lot in roughly 90 minutes.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The GPM scaling is roughly linear: 4.0 GPM is 60 percent faster than 2.5 GPM for the same surface area. For a contractor billing by the job, that 60 percent speed increase directly translates to more jobs per day or lower labor cost per job.</p>

      <h2>Cleaning Units: The Single Number That Eliminates Confusion</h2>
      <p>Because PSI and GPM interact, the industry uses <strong>Cleaning Units (CU)</strong> as a single metric: PSI x GPM = CU. This number correlates strongly with real-world cleaning speed for a given surface and technique.</p>
      <p>Compare the CUs of the machines in this review:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Simpson 4400 PSI / 4.0 GPM:</strong> 17,600 CU — Top-tier commercial cleaning speed. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01KZSGRTE?tag=sciencesolved-20">Check current price</a>.</li>
        <li><strong>Professional 4200 PSI / 4.0 GPM:</strong> 16,800 CU — Nearly identical cleaning speed at a lower price point. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0G6SXZ7VG?tag=sciencesolved-20">Check current price</a>.</li>
        <li><strong>VEVOR 4400 PSI / 4.0 GPM:</strong> 17,600 CU — Matches the Simpson on paper. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0CQQSWJ7Z?tag=sciencesolved-20">Check current price</a>.</li>
        <li><strong>Simpson PS60869 4000 PSI / 3.5 GPM:</strong> 14,000 CU — Strong pro cleaning speed. 20 percent slower than 4.0 GPM class. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07S7H6LGM?tag=sciencesolved-20">Check current price</a>.</li>
        <li><strong>Simpson 3400 PSI / 2.5 GPM:</strong> 8,500 CU — Half the cleaning speed of the 4.0 GPM class. Best for light contractor use. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B086XGSLQC?tag=sciencesolved-20">Check current price</a>.</li>
        <li><strong>Westinghouse ePX3500 Electric 2500 PSI / 1.76 GPM:</strong> 4,400 CU — A quarter of the cleaning speed of a 4.0 GPM gas machine.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The takeaway: a machine with 17,000+ CU cleans roughly twice as fast as a machine with 8,000 CU. That is not marginal. That is the difference between profitable and break-even on large commercial lots.</p>

      <h2>Surface Cleaner Math: GPM Dictates Size</h2>
      <p>This is where GPM becomes the dominant spec. Surface cleaners — the spinning bar attachments used for flat concrete — are sized to match GPM output:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>2.5 GPM:</strong> Use a 10–12-inch surface cleaner maximum. Step up to 14 inches and the cleaner spins too slowly to clean effectively.</li>
        <li><strong>3.5 GPM:</strong> Use a 14–16-inch surface cleaner. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0GPXXGBD2?tag=sciencesolved-20">TOR 14-inch Stainless Steel Surface Cleaner</a> is a perfect match for the Simpson PS60869 at 3.5 GPM.</li>
        <li><strong>4.0 GPM:</strong> Use a 16–20-inch surface cleaner. The wider cleaner doubles the square footage per pass compared to a 12-inch unit.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If you buy a 4.0 GPM machine but pair it with a 12-inch surface cleaner designed for a 2.5 GPM washer, you are leaving 40+ percent of your cleaning speed on the table. Match the surface cleaner size to the actual GPM output for maximum productivity.</p>

      <h2>PSI-Critical Applications vs GPM-Critical Applications</h2>
      <p><strong>When PSI matters most:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Paint and coating stripping — needs 4000 PSI minimum</li>
        <li>Epoxy removal from concrete floors</li>
        <li>Graffiti removal from brick and block</li>
        <li>Rust and heavy oxidation removal from equipment</li>
        <li>Thick gum and tar deposits from parking lots</li>
      </ul>
      <p>For these jobs, prioritize PSI over GPM. A 4000 PSI / 3.5 GPM machine (like the Simpson PS60869) will outperform a 3400 PSI / 4.0 GPM machine because the extra 600 PSI makes the difference between stripping and just wetting the surface.</p>
      <p><strong>When GPM matters most:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Fleet washing — volume flushes away dirt and soap faster</li>
        <li>House washing with downstream chemicals — higher GPM means more chemical coverage per pass</li>
        <li>Large concrete flatwork (parking lots, driveways, warehouse floors)</li>
        <li>Concrete surface preparation before sealing or coating</li>
        <li>General contractor cleanup on large surfaces</li>
      </ul>
      <p>For these jobs, maximize GPM within your budget. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0G6SXZ7VG?tag=sciencesolved-20">Professional 4200 PSI / 4.0 GPM</a> offers the highest GPM at the lowest price point, making it a strong choice for fleet washing and large-area cleaning. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0G6SXZ7VG?tag=sciencesolved-20">Check current price on Amazon</a>.</p>

      <h2>Hydraulics: Why GPM Drops with Distance and Fittings</h2>
      <p>Experienced contractors know that spec-sheet GPM is measured at the pump outlet. By the time water travels through 50 feet of hose, a trigger gun, quick-connect fittings, and a nozzle, actual GPM at the surface drops. The losses come from:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Friction loss in hose:</strong> A 1/4-inch hose loses roughly 5–10 percent of flow per 50 feet at 4.0 GPM. A 3/8-inch hose reduces friction loss significantly — which is why the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07HLMX7BN?tag=sciencesolved-20">YAMATIC 50-foot 3/8 pressure washer hose</a> with steel braiding is a popular upgrade for contractors running 4.0 GPM machines. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07HLMX7BN?tag=sciencesolved-20">Check current price on Amazon</a>.</li>
        <li><strong>Quick-connect restrictions:</strong> Every quick-connect coupling creates a slight flow restriction. Minimize the number of connections between pump and nozzle.</li>
        <li><strong>Nozzle size:</strong> A nozzle that is too small for the GPM creates backpressure that forces the unloader to bypass water. The nozzle orifice must match the machine's GPM output.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If you are running a 4.0 GPM machine through 100 feet of 1/4-inch hose with multiple quick-connect fittings, you may be delivering only 3.2–3.4 GPM at the surface. That is a 15–20 percent reduction in cleaning speed. Upgrade to a 3/8-inch hose like the YAMATIC and minimize connection points to preserve the spec-sheet GPM.</p>

      <h2>Nozzle Selection by PSI and GPM</h2>
      <p>The right nozzle completes the system. Nozzle orifice size is determined by the machine's GPM and the desired pressure. Use this guide:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>4000 PSI / 4.0 GPM:</strong> Use a #4.5 or #5.0 orifice nozzle for general cleaning. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0FH9VJNZ8?tag=sciencesolved-20">Turbo Nozzle Pressure Washer Tips</a> rated at 4000 PSI with 1/4-inch quick connector deliver concentrated rotating impact for stripping — ideal for concrete prep and paint removal. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0FH9VJNZ8?tag=sciencesolved-20">Check current price on Amazon</a>.</li>
        <li><strong>4000 PSI / 3.5 GPM:</strong> Use a #4.0 or #4.5 orifice. The Simpson PS60869 ships with a set of color-coded nozzles that cover 0, 15, 25, and 40-degree spray patterns.</li>
        <li><strong>3400 PSI / 2.5 GPM:</strong> Use a #3.0 or #3.5 orifice. The smaller nozzle conserves the lower flow volume for maximum surface impact.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>A common mistake: using a nozzle with too large an orifice for the machine's GPM. This drops PSI dramatically because the pump cannot maintain pressure against the larger opening. Always match the nozzle orifice to the pump's GPM rating, not the PSI rating.</p>

